Airplane autism is a very particular sort of autism. Basically you progress through the childhood things-that-go phases normally, then just hang up on the airplane obsession and live with it forever. That's how it was for me, and I've heard a few others in the industry describe the same phenomenon. After that most people branch out at least a little bit, but a few just focus. Airplanes also seem to be a common fixation for the legitimately autistic/aspergers. Airports are one of the few places you'll find old guys who seem to have it; pretty sure the guy who let me fly his cub was an aspie. Kind of bizzare, but in practice it usually means you breeze through exams, and if you never get diagnosed, the FAA medical won't bat an eye.

Personally, I try to keep most of my airplane autism out of this thread, but I leave it in my greens where it's relevant. At the moment Silver Lining is a little more autistic than Turkey Shoot, but I think with decent reason. Since I've got both characters operating one airplane, it's not as easy to gloss over procedure, at least early on before they know each other well, as a lot of their interaction hinges on it. Let me know if I dig myself into too much of a hole there. Speaking of, dumping chapter 2 soon.
